The long fast, together with the daily effusion of blood, renders the young girls extremelypale. The chin is not dotted like the other parts, but pierced with one stroke of the thorn in straight lines, upon which musical characters might be written. All thorns seem to have a poisonous quality, and consequently, from being scratched with them, the eyes, cheeks, and lips are horrid- ly swelled, and imbibe a deep black from the ashes placed on the wounded skin3 so that a girl, upon leaving the house of that barbarous old woman, looks like a Stygian fury, and forces you involuntarily to exclaim, Oh! quantum Niobe Niobe distabat ab illst!
